description.narrative: Output 1: By the end of 2019, pregnant women, breastfeeding women and caretakers of under 5 children in the regions of Mopti and Sikasso are aware of the essential actions in nutrition (ENA) and have access to services for prevention of all forms of malnutrition, which contributes to Child Health, Cross-Sectoral Early Childhood Development, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Maternal And Newborn Health, Nutrition â€“ General, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Evaluations, Research And Data, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: [Women and children's nutrition]: By the end of 2019, the nutritional status of children aged 0-59 months and women of childbearing age has improved, especially those living in areas with high prevalence of malnutrition, particularly Mopti and Sikasso.

description.narrative: In 2019, UNICEF supported community mobilization for improved infant and young child feeding (IYCF) and other key family practices. About 1.2 million caregivers and pregnant women were reached through nutrition-related social and behavior change activities conducted by Nutrition Support Groups in four regions. This takes the total number of villages with at least one Nutrition Support Group to 5,270, well above the 2015-2019 CPD target of 4,669. The capacity of 1,680 health workers were built on promotion of IYCF (58 per cent of the targeted number of health workers, below the CPD objective of 60 per cent). | Status:Partially Met | As-of Date:07/02/2020
